From 7d38d585ed5d7ec3c81f1b179b591b2aad73977d Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Johannes Schindelin <johannes.schindelin@gmx.de>
Date: Thu, 2 Apr 2026 15:20:00 +0200
Subject: [PATCH 10/10] perlbug.t: set PERL_BUILD_PACKAGING to avoid XS version
 mismatch

When the test suite runs during a build of a new perl version while an
older perl is already installed, the built-in @INC includes
vendor_perl and site_perl paths from the system installation.  These
directories may contain XS modules (shared libraries) that were
compiled against the old perl's ABI.

perlbug's Init() calls Mail::Util::maildomain(), which lazily loads
Net::SMTP, which in turn loads IO::Socket::SSL and Net::SSLeay at
require time.  If Net::SSLeay's .dll/.so was built for the old perl
(e.g. 5.40) but is loaded into the new perl (e.g. 5.42), the struct
layout mismatch causes an immediate SIGSEGV, making every perlbug.t
subtest return empty output.

perlbug already respects the PERL_BUILD_PACKAGING environment
variable: when set, it marks Mail::Util as unavailable, so Init()
falls back to Sys::Hostname::hostname() for the domain lookup instead
of calling maildomain().  This is correct behavior during a build.

Set PERL_BUILD_PACKAGING=1 in perlbug.t so that every runperl() child
inherits it, keeping the test suite safe from incompatible system XS
modules.
---
 lib/perlbug.t | 11 +++++++++++
 1 file changed, 11 insertions(+)

diff --git a/lib/perlbug.t b/lib/perlbug.t
index b1f876e..42d155c 100644
--- a/lib/perlbug.t
+++ b/lib/perlbug.t
@@ -19,6 +19,17 @@ if (!(-e $extracted_program)) {
     exit 0;
 }
 
+# perlbug consults Mail::Util::maildomain() when it can load Mail::Util
+# and PERL_BUILD_PACKAGING is not set.  maildomain() in turn tries to
+# load Net::SMTP, which pulls in IO::Socket::SSL and Net::SSLeay.
+# When the test suite runs during a build against a *different* perl
+# version that is already installed, the Net::SSLeay XS module picked
+# up from the system vendor_perl was compiled for the old perl and
+# crashes with a SIGSEGV.  Setting PERL_BUILD_PACKAGING makes perlbug
+# skip the maildomain() call (falling back to Sys::Hostname), which is
+# the right thing to do during a build anyway.
+$ENV{PERL_BUILD_PACKAGING} = 1;
+
 my $result;
 my $testreport = 'test.rep';
 unlink $testreport;
